<br>
&quot;Actually, it was not found illegal to put up a statue of the ten commandments in a public place. The context of which the judge did so was the problem, not the ten commandments themself. It is entirely possible for a ten commandments monument to be constructed at a court house and still be within the law and constitutional. However, the circumstances were obviously not such in this case.&quot;<br>
<br>
It is only entirely possible for this to happen if noone finds fault in it, and if it isn't done by a government official. <br>
<br>
That is to say, the &quot;circumstances&quot; you are referring to are of non-Ten Commandment believing lawyers who felt insulted and belittled by this monument asserting that the court was secondary to the &quot;house of god.&quot; This was manifest through the disallowance of other religious viewpoints which would sully such stature.<br>
<br>
Of course, it would be legal if they allow every other religion to have their own codex represented... it would also be &quot;legal&quot; if noone ever complained or cared to petition or file.<br>
<br>
This is all in the 50 page document which you are citing.<br>
<br>
Mr. 10 Commandments wants &quot;any governmental action promoting religion in general or a particular religion [to be] free from constitutional scrutiny.&quot; This is so, so very not true. It is illegal for a statue of the 10 commandments to be placed in public by any government official.<br>
<br>
