<br>
&quot;Now onto Legalities of the issue if you want to get into that. The Supreme Court has held that words which ‘by their very utterance inflict injury or tend to incite an immediate breach in the peace’ are not protected by the First Amendment. Though granted the First Amendment reads “Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof; or abridging the freedom of speech, or of the press; or the right of the people peaceably to assemble, and to petition the government for a redress of grievances.”&quot;<br>
<br>
Well, exactly: how are people who are not of a religion that recognizes the 10 commandments going to peaceably assemble inside? It sets up an Us &amp; Them relationship, demoralizes, and otherwise underhandedly excludes.<br>
<br>
Sure, it says &quot;Congress&quot; Mr. 10 Commandments argues, but somehow he wants his own station of government to be exempt from constitutional law. It will only happen as long as noone challenges the law.<br>
<br>
